1 than five hundred dollars ($500) per violation.
2 (10) It shall not be necessary that actual damages be alleged or proved in order to
3 recover any other remedy or penalty authorized under this section.
4 (11) (a) The remedies and penalties prescribed in this section shall be cumulative.
5 (b) Nothing in this section shall be construed to limit or restrict the powers,
6 duties, remedies, or penalties available to the Attorney General, the
7 Commonwealth, or any other person under any other statutory or common
8 law.
9 (12) The Attorney General may promulgate administrative regulations in accordance
10 with KRS Chapter 13A that are necessary to effectuate, or as an aid to the
11 effectuation of, the enforcement of this section.
12 Section 2. KRS 304.14-410 is amended to read as follows:
13 No insurer shall use an itemized statement furnished pursuant to Section 1 of this
14 Act[KRS 216B.250] for insurance payment purposes where benefits have been assigned.
15 Section 3. KRS 304.32-1551 is amended to read as follows:
16 No corporation subject to the provisions of this subtitle shall use an itemized statement
17 furnished pursuant to Section 1 of this Act[KRS 216B.250] for insurance payment
18 purposes where benefits have been assigned.
19 Section 4. KRS 214.556 is amended to read as follows:
20 (1) There is hereby established within the Kentucky cancer program the Kentucky
21 Cancer Registry and the cancer patient data management system for the purpose of
22 providing accurate and up-to-date information about cancer in Kentucky and
23 facilitating the evaluation and improvement of cancer prevention, screening,
24 diagnosis, therapy, rehabilitation, and community care activities for citizens of the
25 Commonwealth. The cancer patient data management system shall be administered
26 by the Lucille Parker Markey Cancer Center.
27 (2) Each licensed health facility which provides diagnostic services, or diagnostic
Page 9 of 13
XXXX 12/19/2025 1:59 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 80
1 services and treatment, or treatment to cancer patients shall report to the Kentucky
2 Cancer Registry, through the cancer patient data management system and in a
3 format prescribed by the Kentucky Cancer Registry, each case of cancer seen at that
4 health facility. Failure to comply may be cause for assessment of an administrative
5 fine for the health facility, the same as the civil penalty for a violation of Section 1
6 of this Act[KRS 216B.250].
7 (3) Each health facility shall grant to the cancer registry access to all records which
8 would identify cases of cancer or would establish characteristics of the cancer,
9 treatment of the cancer, or status of any identified cancer patient. Hospitals actively
10 participating and enrolled in the cancer patient data management system of the
11 Kentucky Cancer Program as of July 13, 1990, shall be considered to be in
12 compliance with this section. The Lucille Parker Markey Cancer Center shall
13 provide staff assistance in compiling and reporting required information to hospitals
14 which treat a low volume of patients.
15 (4) No liability of any kind or character for damages or other relief shall arise or be
16 enforced against any licensed health facility by reason of having provided the
17 information or material to the Kentucky Cancer Registry pursuant to the
18 requirements of this section.
19 (5) The identity of any person whose condition or treatment has been reported to the
20 Kentucky Cancer Registry shall be confidential, except that:
21 (a) The Kentucky Cancer Registry may exchange patient-specific data with any
22 other cancer control agency or clinical facility for the purpose of obtaining
23 information necessary to complete a case record, but the agency or clinical
24 facility shall not further disclose such personal data; and
25 (b) The Kentucky Cancer Registry may contact individual patients if necessary to
26 obtain follow-up information which is not available from the health facility.
27 (6) All information, interviews, reports, statements, memoranda, or other data furnished
Page 10 of 13
XXXX 12/19/2025 1:59 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 80
1 by reason of this section, expressly including all portions, subsets, extracts, or
2 compilations of the data as well as any findings or conclusions resulting from those
3 studies, shall be privileged and shall not be considered public records under KRS
4 61.870 to 61.884. The Kentucky Cancer Registry may determine that certain
5 extracts, subsets, or compilations of data do not reveal privileged information and
6 may be published or otherwise shared to further the public health goals set forth
7 herein.
8 (7) The Kentucky Cancer Registry shall make periodic reports of its data and any
9 related findings and recommendations to the Legislative Research Commission, the
10 Interim Joint Committees on Appropriations and Revenue and Health Services, the
11 Governor, the Cabinet for Health and Family Services, the reporting health facility,
12 and other appropriate governmental and nongovernmental cancer control agencies
13 whose intent it is to reduce the incidence, morbidity, and mortality of cancer. The
14 Kentucky Cancer Registry may conduct analyses and studies as are indicated to
15 advance cancer control in the Commonwealth, either directly or by confidentially
16 sharing data with third parties.
17 Section 5. KRS 216B.990 is amended to read as follows:
18 (1) Any person who, in willful violation of this chapter, operates a health facility or
19 abortion facility without first obtaining a license or continues to operate a health
20 facility or abortion facility after a final decision suspending or revoking a license
21 shall be fined not less than five hundred dollars ($500) nor more than ten thousand
22 dollars ($10,000) for each violation.
23 (2) Any person who, in willful violation of this chapter, acquires major medical
24 equipment, establishes a health facility, or obligates a capital expenditure without
25 first obtaining a certificate of need, or after the applicable certificate of need has
26 been withdrawn, shall be fined one percent (1%) of the capital expenditure involved
27 but not less than five hundred dollars ($500) for each violation.
Page 11 of 13
XXXX 12/19/2025 1:59 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 80
1 (3) Any health care provider or hospital acting by or through its agents or employees
2 which violates any provision of KRS 216B.400 shall be punished by a fine of not
3 less than one hundred dollars ($100) nor more than five hundred dollars ($500). The
4 cabinet shall establish an online portal on its website for reporting violations of
5 KRS 216B.400.
6 (4) [Any health facility which willfully violates KRS 216B.250 shall be fined one
7 hundred dollars ($100) per day for failure to post required notices and one hundred
8 dollars ($100) per instance for willfully failing to provide an itemized statement
9 within the required time frames.
10 (5) ]In addition to the civil penalties established under KRS 216B.306(1) and (4), any
11 person who advertises, solicits boarders, or operates a boarding home without first
12 obtaining a registration as required by KRS 216B.305 and any person who aids or
13 abets the operation of a boarding home that is not registered shall be imprisoned for
14 no more than twelve (12) months.
15 (5)[(6)] Any person or entity establishing, managing, or operating an abortion facility
16 or conducting the business of an abortion facility which otherwise violates any
17 provision of this chapter or any administrative regulation promulgated thereunder
18 regarding abortion facilities shall be subject to revocation or suspension of the
19 license of the abortion facility. In addition, any violation of any provision of this
20 chapter regarding abortion facilities or any administrative regulation related thereto
21 by intent, fraud, deceit, unlawful design, willful and deliberate misrepresentation, or
22 by careless, negligent, or incautious disregard for the statute or administrative
23 regulation, either by persons acting individually or in concert with others, shall
24 constitute a violation and shall be punishable by a fine not to exceed one thousand
25 dollars ($1,000) for each offense. Each day of continuing violation shall be
26 considered a separate offense. The venue for prosecution of the violation shall be in
27 any county of the state in which the violation, or any portion thereof, occurred.
